WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.080
I am here to talk about time, which is obviously everyone's favorite subject.

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:14.420
In particular, I'm actually here to talk about a package called Clock.

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:18.920
So Clock is a date-time manipulation library, kind of in the same way that Lubridate is

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:21.040
a date-time manipulation library.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:25.280
It does things you might expect, add dates, subtract dates, format and parse them, all

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:27.879
kinds of other manipulation.

00:00:27.879 --> 00:00:33.160
But if you get anything out of this talk, it's really that Clock is not here to replace

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:35.119
Lubridate in any way.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:40.279
The only idea would be that, in the end, Clock might be a back-end for Lubridate, in the

00:00:40.279 --> 00:00:46.439
same way that DTPlier or DBPlier are different types of back-ends for DPlier.

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:49.919
And I'm not even going to spend the rest of this talk talking about features that overlap

00:00:49.919 --> 00:00:50.919
with Lubridate.

00:00:50.919 --> 00:00:55.200
Instead, I want to talk about things that are pretty unique to Clock.

00:00:55.200 --> 00:01:01.520
One of those is safety, and one of those is calendars, because I only have five minutes.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:08.400
I'm going to do that with one date, January 30th of this year.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:13.879
Safety is built into Clock from the ground up to hopefully avoid issues like this, time

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:17.760
zone issues, invalid date issues, things that are pretty common when you're working with

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.360
time series and just drive you up the wall.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:23.519
So let's jump into safety.

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:24.800
Here's a timeline.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:29.680
This is January 30th, our date in question, marked in blue on our timeline.

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:32.480
It continues through to February on the next line.

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:37.919
You'll see this gap between February and March, because February only has 28 days, but January

00:01:37.919 --> 00:01:40.919
had 31, so it doesn't necessarily map one-to-one.

00:01:40.919 --> 00:01:48.400
If I were to ask you this seemingly innocuous question, please add one month to this date,

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:50.400
what would you get?

00:01:50.879 --> 00:01:55.919
Well, if we were to ask LuberDate, it gives you a somewhat reasonable answer of NA.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:02:03.239
There is nothing that maps one-to-one from January 30th to something in February, maybe.

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:08.039
And there's nothing particularly wrong with this, except for the fact that it's not the

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:09.960
most useful answer.

00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:15.639
Generally, you'll be running this code, and it happens silently, and then five steps downstream,

00:02:15.639 --> 00:02:18.880
all of a sudden you discover there's some NAs here?

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:20.279
I didn't have those to begin with.

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:21.279
Where did those come from?

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:27.119
And you have to backtrack up through your calculations to figure out why they appeared.

00:02:27.119 --> 00:02:32.279
If you were to ask clock this question with add months, it actually gives you an error

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:34.440
in this special case by default.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.039
It says, whoa, hold up, there's something wrong here.

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:38.639
Go look at location one.

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:42.520
If you had a vector, it might be location five, seven, whatever.

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:46.360
And check out the invalid argument to learn more about this case.

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:50.520
You go and you look at the documentation, and you come out with the idea that maybe

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:54.300
I could set this thing called invalid equals previous.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:03:00.440
That allows you to say, give me the previous valid date when I have this kind of problem.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:01.440
That's the end of February.

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:05.100
I think that's a pretty reasonable result in this case.

00:03:05.100 --> 00:03:10.179
But you also might want to say, depending on your specific problem, invalid equals next

00:03:10.179 --> 00:03:14.119
to map forward to the beginning of March instead.

00:03:14.119 --> 00:03:18.960
If you actually do like that behavior, that's fine, you can say invalid equals NA, and any

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:22.919
time that occurs, you get an NA instead.

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:24.820
So that's about safety.

00:03:24.820 --> 00:03:27.479
Let's talk about calendars.

00:03:27.479 --> 00:03:32.759
Calendars are just the idea of a way to represent a unique point in time.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:38.759
With our date in question, we could use a calendar called year, month, day to represent

00:03:38.759 --> 00:03:43.240
this date using three components, the year, the month, and the day of the month.

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:46.460
But this isn't the only way you could represent this date.

00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:50.679
You could also use the year and the day of the year.

00:03:50.679 --> 00:03:56.539
Or you could use one of these many other calendar types that are built into Clock.

00:03:56.539 --> 00:04:01.240
If you're a finance person, you might be particularly interested in year, quarter, day, which uses

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:07.039
a true fiscal year to represent your date.

00:04:07.039 --> 00:04:10.440
These are really nice because they're all convertible to each other.

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:14.479
You can work with any particular calendar type and say you need to get the quarter out,

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:18.519
you convert to year, quarter, day, you do manipulation over there, you convert back.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:24.160
It's obviously convertible with date and POSIX-CT as well, since those are the date time types

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.079
that you're most likely to start out with.

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:32.839
The other really neat thing that I find really fun about these calendar types is that they

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:35.959
have what's known as variable precision.

00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:41.119
These are all day precision calendar types at this point, but we could narrow that down

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:47.000
to month precision as needed, and you've got a built-in year, month type in Clock.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.480
Similarly, you could have a built-in year, quarter type.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:52.239
You can actually go the other way, too.

00:04:52.239 --> 00:04:58.440
You can widen it out all the way to nanoseconds if you need it.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:03.119
The last thing I'll say is that Clock is completely compatible with some of the other packages

00:05:03.239 --> 00:05:08.320
you might be familiar with that I've created, called Slider and IVs.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:13.839
Slider is one for rolling averages, so you can use Clock types as the index to say give

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:17.640
me a rolling average looking back four or five quarters.

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:22.519
IVs is a relatively new package, you might not have heard of this one yet, but it deals

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:29.679
with date ranges, and you can use Clock types as the components of those ranges.

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:35.119
So to sum up, LuberDate is not going anywhere, don't worry, but please try Clock for enhanced

00:05:35.119 --> 00:05:37.679
safety and these powerful new types.

00:05:37.679 --> 00:05:38.679
Thank you.

00:05:38.679 --> 00:05:39.679
Thank you.

00:05:39.679 --> 00:05:39.679


